# argus — AWS real-deploy prep sheet. Fill a COPY of this, then source it before the two populate helpers:
#
#   cp infra/aws/scripts/prep.env.example infra/aws/scripts/prep.env
#   # …edit prep.env, fill every <…>…
#   set -a; . infra/aws/scripts/prep.env; set +a       # export everything
#   infra/aws/scripts/populate-keyvault.sh             # uses the ARGUS_* externals below
#   infra/aws/scripts/setup-github-cicd.sh             # uses the S3_*/OIDC_*/VITE_OIDC_* below
#
# ORDER: this runs AFTER `terraform apply` (the vault + EC2 must exist; GitHub values come from terraform
# output) and BEFORE you flip ENABLE_DEPLOY_AWS + push the aws-v0.1.0 tag. See infra/aws/terraform/README.md.
#
# SECURITY: your filled `prep.env` holds live secrets — NEVER commit it (gitignore it), keep it 0600, delete
# it after the deploy. The helpers themselves never put a secret on a command line.

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# A) populate-keyvault.sh — the 4 EXTERNAL credentials it can't generate (everything else is auto-generated).
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# B2 ATTACHMENTS bucket — the SECRET half of its S3 application key.
#   Backblaze → Account → Application Keys → the attachments-bucket key. The "keyID" is non-secret and goes in
#   S3_ACCESS_KEY_ID below; this is the "applicationKey" (secret) shown ONCE at creation.
ARGUS_S3_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=<b2-attachments-applicationKey>

# B2 DB-BACKUPS bucket — its application key (separate key, used by the nightly pg_dump backup).
#   Backblaze → Application Keys → the db-backups-bucket key (the applicationKey string).
ARGUS_B2_APP_KEY=<b2-db-backups-applicationKey>

# Cloudflare Tunnel token — Zero Trust → Networks → Tunnels → your tunnel → Configure → the token string
#   (the value after `cloudflared service install`). This is how ingress reaches the box with no public ports.
ARGUS_TUNNEL_TOKEN=<cloudflare-tunnel-token>

# GHCR pull token — a GitHub PAT to pull the published images on the EC2 box.
#   Classic PAT with `read:packages`, or a fine-grained token with Packages: read on this repo's packages.
ARGUS_GHCR_TOKEN=<github-pat-read-packages>

# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# B) setup-github-cicd.sh — config it can't derive from terraform output (the AWS bits are auto-pulled).
#    These become repo VARIABLES (not secrets); S3_ACCESS_KEY_ID is non-secret (rides in every presigned URL).
# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# B2 ATTACHMENTS bucket name + the keyID half of the key whose secret you put in ARGUS_S3_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY.
S3_BUCKET=<b2-attachments-bucket-name>
S3_ACCESS_KEY_ID=<b2-attachments-keyID>

# Zitadel OIDC (self-hosted in the stack). ISSUER = your Zitadel base URL (the auth hostname behind the tunnel,
# e.g. https://auth.<your-domain>). AUDIENCE = the audience the API expects in the token (your Zitadel project
# / API resource id). NOTE: the SPA CLIENT_ID below only exists once Zitadel is up and you've created the app —
# on a first deploy you may set a placeholder, bring the stack up, configure Zitadel, then re-set
# VITE_OIDC_CLIENT_ID and rebuild the web bundle. The issuer + redirect URI you know in advance.
OIDC_ISSUER=https://auth.<your-domain>
OIDC_AUDIENCE=<zitadel-api-audience-or-project-id>
VITE_OIDC_ISSUER=https://auth.<your-domain>
VITE_OIDC_CLIENT_ID=<zitadel-spa-pkce-client-id>
VITE_OIDC_REDIRECT_URI=https://<app-hostname>/auth/callback

# ── Optional (sensible defaults if you leave them unset) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# X42C_API_TOKEN=<42crunch-platform-token>   # only if you want the API audit (also flip ENABLE_42CRUNCH=true)
# GHCR_USER=Dezoxy                            # default = repo owner
# S3_ENDPOINT=https://s3.eu-central-003.backblazeb2.com   # default = B2 eu-central-003
# S3_REGION=eu-central-003                     # default = B2 eu-central-003
# GH_REVIEWER_ID=<numeric-github-user-id>      # default = the authenticated gh user (the env's required reviewer)
# GITHUB_DEPLOY_ENVIRONMENT=aws-experiment     # MUST match var.github_deploy_environment in Terraform
